Step 1 — NodeErrorReport Dataclass
Purpose

The existing errors dictionary in the project only represented:

Collector/runtime failures

Examples:

pdsh failed
file read failed
command execution failed

However, the new requirement introduces:

Actual infrastructure failures

Examples:

iSCSI connection loss
I/O errors
storage disconnects
network timeouts

These are fundamentally different concepts.

Implementation
from dataclasses import dataclass

@dataclass
class NodeErrorReport:
    node: str
    source: str
    severity: str
    message: str
Why This Structure Matters

This dataclass defines the diagnostic model used throughout the system.

Instead of storing raw strings:

all_errors.append(line)

we now store structured diagnostics:

NodeErrorReport(
    node="worker-1",
    source="iscsi",
    severity="critical",
    message="session recovery failed"
)
Field Explanation
Field	Purpose
node	Which node produced the issue
source	Which subsystem produced the issue
severity	How serious the issue is
message	Actual log/error message
Why Use @dataclass

Benefits:

cleaner code
structured access
easier serialization
maintainability
extensibility

Example:

error.node

instead of:

error["node"]
Step 2 — ERROR_PATTERNS
Purpose

After collecting logs, the CLI still only sees:

Raw text

The system needs a way to determine:

what is important
what is dangerous
which subsystem is affected

This is done using pattern-based diagnostics detection.

Implementation
ERROR_PATTERNS = [
    {
        "pattern": r"connection.*lost",
        "severity": "warning",
        "source": "iscsi",
    },
    {
        "pattern": r"session.*failure",
        "severity": "warning",
        "source": "iscsi",
    },
    {
        "pattern": r"timed out",
        "severity": "warning",
        "source": "network",
    },
    {
        "pattern": r"blocked for more than",
        "severity": "critical",
        "source": "kernel",
    },
    {
        "pattern": r"I/O error",
        "severity": "critical",
        "source": "storage",
    },
    {
        "pattern": r"rejecting I/O to offline device",
        "severity": "critical",
        "source": "storage",
    },
]
Why Regex Is Used

System logs vary across:

Linux distributions
kernel versions
storage stacks

Exact matching is fragile.

Regex allows flexible matching.

Example:

r"connection.*lost"

matches:

connection lost
connection unexpectedly lost
iscsi connection lost
Why Centralized Rules Matter

Instead of:

if "timed out" in line:
elif "connection lost" in line:

all rules are stored centrally.

Benefits:

easier maintenance
cleaner parsing logic
scalable detection system
simpler future expansion
Step 3 — collect_recent_logs()
Purpose

The CLI now needs to gather logs from:

iSCSI target nodes
initiator nodes

However, different Linux environments store logs differently.

Examples:

RHEL → /var/log/messages
Ubuntu → /var/log/syslog
systemd environments → journalctl
minimal systems → dmesg

The collector must support all common environments.

Implementation
def collect_recent_logs(
    node: str,
    lines: int = 200,
) -> Tuple[str, Optional[str]]:
    commands = [
        f"journalctl -n {lines} --no-pager 2>/dev/null",
        f"tail -n {lines} /var/log/messages 2>/dev/null",
        f"tail -n {lines} /var/log/syslog 2>/dev/null",
        f"dmesg | tail -n {lines}",
    ]

    for command in commands:
        output, error = run_pdsh_text(
            f'pdsh -w {node} "{command}"'
        )

        if output:
            return output, None

    return "", f"{node}: unable to collect logs"
Why Use Fallback Collection

Different systems expose logs differently.

This fallback chain ensures:

better portability
distro compatibility
more reliable diagnostics
Why Keep It Simple

The implementation intentionally avoids:

streaming log collectors
async log pipelines
external logging agents

The goal is:

operational simplicity
maintainability
CLI-focused diagnostics
Step 4 — scan_logs_for_errors()
Purpose

After collecting logs, the CLI must:

inspect log lines
detect known failures
classify them
convert them into structured diagnostics
Implementation
def scan_logs_for_errors(
    node: str,
    log_text: str,
) -> List[NodeErrorReport]:
    findings: List[NodeErrorReport] = []

    for line in log_text.splitlines():
        lowered = line.lower()

        for entry in ERROR_PATTERNS:
            if re.search(entry["pattern"], lowered, re.IGNORECASE):
                findings.append(
                    NodeErrorReport(
                        node=node,
                        source=entry["source"],
                        severity=entry["severity"],
                        message=line.strip(),
                    )
                )

    return findings
How It Works
Step 1

Split logs into lines:

log_text.splitlines()
Step 2

Iterate over every log line.

Step 3

Compare each line against every detection rule.

Step 4

Create structured diagnostic reports.

Why Structured Parsing Matters

Without parsing:

logs remain noisy
operators must inspect manually
automation becomes difficult

Structured diagnostics enable:

filtering
reporting
alerting
severity grouping
Step 5 — Initiator Node Support
Problem

The original CLI only discovers:

iscsi-target=true

However, storage/network issues can occur on:

initiator nodes
worker nodes
client nodes

Diagnostics must support both sides.

Implementation
DEFAULT_INITIATOR_SELECTOR = "iscsi-initiator=true"

CLI option:

parser.add_argument(
    "--initiator-selector",
    default=DEFAULT_INITIATOR_SELECTOR,
    help="Kubernetes label selector used to discover iSCSI initiator nodes",
)
Why Separate Selectors

Target nodes and initiator nodes serve different roles.

Keeping separate selectors:

preserves flexibility
avoids assumptions
supports mixed environments
Step 6 — collect_node_diagnostics()
Purpose

This function combines:

log collection
log scanning
diagnostics generation

into one reusable diagnostics workflow.

Implementation
def collect_node_diagnostics(
    node: str,
) -> Tuple[List[NodeErrorReport], List[str]]:
    errors: List[str] = []

    logs, log_error = collect_recent_logs(node)

    if log_error:
        return [], [log_error]

    findings = scan_logs_for_errors(node, logs)

    return findings, errors
Why This Abstraction Is Useful

This creates a reusable diagnostics pipeline.

The main collection flow only needs:

diagnostics, diagnostic_errors = collect_node_diagnostics(node)

instead of managing:

log collection
parsing
rule matching
diagnostics construction

separately.
